<div class=3D"available-content"><div dir=3D"auto" class=3D"body markup"><p=
><span>Louise Perry is one of my favorite writers=E2=80=94if you haven=E2=
=80=99t yet, I strongly recommend subscribing to </span><a href=3D"https://=
www.louiseperry.co.uk/" rel=3D"">her Substack</a><span>. </span></p><p>We d=
id a livestream recently covering a lot of ground: </p><ul><li><p>Louise sh=
ares how being neurotic can actually be adaptive when raising kids, even if=
 it means worrying about choking hazards or obsessing over safety devices.<=
/p></li><li><p>Louise asks me about the "secret sauce" for kids who overcom=
e trauma and neglect, sparking a thoughtful comparison between my journey a=
nd J.D. Vance's. I share some of my riskier choices growing up, reflecting =
on how low neuroticism can be as dangerous as it is freeing.</p></li><li><p=
>We dive into a classic debate=E2=80=94how much of resilience is about raw =
attributes, and how much comes from the environment you're thrown into?</p>=
</li><li><p>We discuss a study indicating that physical strength accounts f=
or some of the sex differences in neuroticism=E2=80=94and what that might m=
ean for men, women, and survival strategies. There=E2=80=99s some truth to =
stereotypes. We talk about studies indicating that height and physicality p=
redicts political views, and what this says about human nature.</p></li><li=
><p><span>Some research </span><a href=3D"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/f=
ull/10.1080/09515089.2021.1946026" rel=3D"">indicates</a><span> that people=
 high on the Dark Triad personality traits are more likely to endorse antin=
atalist views (the opinion that it=E2=80=99s wrong to have children). I sug=
gest that antinatalism might be a mating interference strategy for people w=
ith =E2=80=9Cdark=E2=80=9D personality traits. They (unconsciously) try to =
convince you not to have children in order to conserve resources for themse=
lves and their own offspring. Similarly, the judgment against large familie=
s in affluent circles might also be an evolutionary mating interference str=
ategy, subtly discouraging reproductive competition.</span></p></li><li><p>=
Louise and I discuss how declining birth rates may be shaping the genetic a=
nd psychological traits of future generations=E2=80=94and what traits we mi=
ght be "selecting" without realizing it.</p></li><li><p>The reversal of the=
 Flynn effect, large cities as "IQ shredders," and how the pursuit of ambit=
ion might be thinning the ranks of highly intelligent parents.</p></li></ul=
><div class=3D"paywall-jump" data-component-name=3D"PaywallToDOM"></div><ul=
><li><p>I suggest that there might be a critical developmental window for b=
ecoming comfortable around infants. Growing up around babies might be essen=
tial for adults to feel comfortable with them=E2=80=94something increasingl=
y rare in modern life.</p></li><li><p>How religious traditions that elevate=
 motherhood and family formation might have evolved to counteract natural a=
mbivalence toward having children.</p></li><li><p>Louise proposes that Musk=
=E2=80=99s pro-natalist, boundary-pushing ambitions align with a uniquely B=
ritish Victorian industrialist tradition of exploration and colonization.</=
p></li><li><p>We reflect on how cultural shifts, like the "cool girl" ideal=
, discouraged women from seeking commitment, leaving many stuck in "situati=
onships."</p></li><li><p>Louise explains J.D. Unwin=E2=80=99s controversial=
 theory that sexual permissiveness leads to societal decline, which has str=
iking parallels with modern trends.</p></li><li><p><span>I reference Mark R=
egnerus=E2=80=99s book </span><em>Cheap Sex</em><span>, and we examine how =
easy access to casual sex and porn has reduced men=E2=80=99s motivation to =
pursue marriage, careers, and societal contributions.</span></p></li><li><p=
>Much more in the conversation</p></li></ul><p>Join me for my next live vid=
eo in the app:</p><div class=3D"install-substack-app-embed install-substack=
