span>I am pro choice, but I wonder if being high on the Dark Triad makes pe=
ople more likely to be pro "choice". The people I've met in pro choice acti=
vism have been horrific: narcissistic, bullying, cruel, and vulgar. Whereas=
 the people I've met who volunteer at Crisis Pregnancy Centers - where they=
 discourage abortion and provide up to two years of free baby supplies and =
connection to social service resources - have been kind, generous, and lovi=
ng - even toward pro choice people like myself.</span></p><p><span>This mak=
es me wonder if the pro choice movement has been losing ground due to its d=
omination by people high on the Dark Triad. </span></p><p><span>I was kicke=
d out of the Texas Handmaids in a very nasty and "mean girl" way for sugges=
ting the claim that "men need abortions, too" was ridiculous and alienating=
 to most people. I also objected to gross signs that said "Honk if you love=
 pizza and abortion!" </span></p><p><span>I had an abortion and it was the =
right choice for me at the time, but I still grieve it and have conflicting=
 feelings about it. </span></p><p><span>I also think abortion on demand sho=
uld be limited to the first 12 to 15 weeks of pregnancy, and limited to ris=
k to the mother's health after that.</span></p><p><span>But too many people=
 in the pro choice movement are extremely cavalier in their support of abor=
tion - some are even gleeful about it. How can anyone be gleeful about dest=
roying an incipient human life? </span></p><p><span>Anyway, I have seen a l=
ot of anecdotal evidence that Dark Triad personalities dominate the pro cho=
ice movement as well as the antinatal movement.</span></p><div role=3D"butt=
