tton></div></div><div class=3D"comment-body"><p><span>I just listened to th=
e discussion. Once again, I am annoyed by the stereotype that poor people h=
ave more children because the =E2=80=9Cwelfare state=E2=80=9D incentivizes =
this.  Perhaps that is the case in the UK, but the =E2=80=9Cwelfare=E2=80=
=9D options in Cleveland, Ohio, where I have worked as a mental health coun=
selor with low income clients for 30 years, are certainly not rewarding.  A=
ny cash assistance is extremely low and limited to a few months, certainly =
not anything that you could support yourself and a child on.  You have to w=
ork unless you can depend on family to provide support.  You cannot depend =
on the father of the child to offer any support. You can get a voucher for =
child care so you can work, but,hopefully, you can keep your job long enoug=
h to wade through the red tape to get approved. You can get food stamps, bu=
t usually not  enough, especially if your low paying job pays you just a li=
ttle too much.  Since you cannot afford rent with your low paying job, you =
can apply for subsidized housing if you can wait two to five years for the =
funds to be available. The one advantage is that you qualify for Medicaid w=
hich will pay for you to have a baby. But, again, if you make a little too =
much, you will lose that necessary support. But it doesn=E2=80=99t cover an=
 abortion, so maybe that is how the welfare state allows the poor to have m=
ore children. It has been rare for the poor women that I have worked with t=
hrough the years to have more than one or two children.  So please stop ref=
erring to welfare as an explanation for why the poor have more children.  I=
f they do, the reasons are not because welfare makes it so easy.  </span></=
