ody"><p><span>I have another angle on the sexual repression/successful soci=
eties discussion, if it's any use.  "Repressive" societies counterintuitive=
ly allow for access to significantly more sex, at a lower cost.  Marriage i=
s tough to get, but once you're married, you're good for life.  "Permissive=
" societies have a lower up-front cost for sex, sure, but partnerships are =
also significantly shorter term, and far less reliable, which means that th=
e cost never really decreases, or goes away.</span></p><p><span>To give a k=
ind of weird comparison, repressive societies are encouraging people to buy=
 houses, while permissive ones encourage renting.  The initial cost of buyi=
ng hurts, and everyone complains about it, but ultimately it's a much sound=
er investment.  Renters gain variety at a cost to basically everything else=
.  They spend more time shopping around, spend less time improving the plac=
e that they live, and ultimately spend far more money than buyers do, all w=
hile ending up in a lower quality living space.</span></p><p><span>People s=
ee the big price tag on marriage and they automatically think it's restrict=
ive, but that's not entirely fair.  The main thing it represses is partner =
variety.  In terms of relationship depth/stability, quantity of sex, and th=
e amount of romantic effort your partner expects, marriage is very freeing.=
  Plus, you aren't locked in a state of constant competition with every oth=
er member of your sex for decades, which makes it much easier to approach h=
umanity with a cooperative spirit.  Teamwork makes the dream work, so they =
say.</span></p><div role=3D"button" class=3D"show-all-toggle"><div class=3D=
